{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"The fragrance that you will smell, you will never be able to smell this way again."},{"time":4000,"text":"It’s a fragrance called Beyond Paradise,"},{"time":7000,"text":"which you can find in any store in the nation."},{"time":10000,"text":"Except here it’s been split up in parts by Estée Lauder"},{"time":14000,"text":"and by the perfumer who did it, Calice Becker,\n"},{"time":17000,"text":"and I'm most grateful to them for this."},{"time":18000,"text":"And it’s been split up in successive bits and a chord."}]},{"cues":[{"time":22000,"text":"So what you’re smelling now is the top note."},{"time":24000,"text":"And then will come what they call the heart, the lush heart note."},{"time":28000,"text":"I will show it to you."},{"time":31000,"text":"The Eden top note is named after the Eden Project in the U.K."}]},{"cues":[{"time":34000,"text":"The lush heart note, Melaleuca bark note -- which does not contain any Melaleuca bark,"},{"time":39000,"text":"because it’s totally forbidden."}]},{"cues":[{"time":42000,"text":"And after that, the complete fragrance."},{"time":45000,"text":"Now what you are smelling is a combination of --"},{"time":48000,"text":"I asked how many molecules there were in there, and nobody would tell me."},{"time":52000,"text":"So I put it through a G.C., a Gas Chromatograph that I have in my office,"},{"time":57000,"text":"and it’s about 400."},{"time":60000,"text":"So what you’re smelling is several hundred molecules"},{"time":63000,"text":"floating through the air, hitting your nose."}]},{"cues":[{"time":66000,"text":"And do not get the impression that this is very subjective."},{"time":70000,"text":"You are all smelling pretty much the same thing, OK?"},{"time":74000,"text":"Smell has this reputation of being somewhat different for each person."},{"time":78000,"text":"It’s not really true."},{"time":79000,"text":"And perfumery shows you that can’t be true,"},{"time":81000,"text":"because if it were like that it wouldn’t be an art, OK?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":87000,"text":"Now, while the smell wafts over you, let me tell you the history of an idea."},{"time":91000,"text":"Everything that you’re smelling in here"},{"time":95000,"text":"is made up of atoms that come from what I call"},{"time":97000,"text":"the Upper East Side of the periodic table -- a nice, safe neighborhood."},{"time":100000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":104000,"text":"You really don’t want to leave it if you want to have a career in perfumery."},{"time":107000,"text":"Some people have tried in the 1920s"},{"time":109000,"text":"to add things from the bad parts, and it didn’t really work."}]},{"cues":[{"time":113000,"text":"These are the five atoms from which just about everything"},{"time":115000,"text":"that you’re going to smell in real life, from coffee to fragrance, are made of."},{"time":121000,"text":"The top note that you smelled at the very beginning,"},{"time":123000,"text":"the cut-grass green, what we call in perfumery -- they’re weird terms --"},{"time":127000,"text":"and this would be called a green note,"},{"time":129000,"text":"because it smells of something green, like cut grass."}]},{"cues":[{"time":131000,"text":"This is cis-3-hexene-1-ol. And I had to learn chemistry on the fly"},{"time":138000,"text":"in the last three years. A very expensive high school chemistry education."},{"time":144000,"text":"This has six carbon atoms, so \"hexa,\" hexene-1-ol."},{"time":148000,"text":"It has one double bond, it has an alcohol on the end,"},{"time":152000,"text":"so it’s \"ol,\" and that’s why they call it cis-3-hexene-1-ol."},{"time":155000,"text":"Once you figure this out, you can really impress people at parties."}]},{"cues":[{"time":158000,"text":"This smells of cut grass. Now, this is the skeleton of the molecule."},{"time":162000,"text":"If you dress it up with atoms, hydrogen atoms --"},{"time":165000,"text":"that’s what it looks like when you have it on your computer --"},{"time":167000,"text":"but actually it’s sort of more like this, in the sense that the atoms have a certain"},{"time":171000,"text":"sphere that you cannot penetrate. They repel."}]},{"cues":[{"time":174000,"text":"OK, now. Why does this thing smell of cut grass, OK?"},{"time":180000,"text":"Why doesn’t it smell of potatoes or violets? Well, there are really two theories."},{"time":186000,"text":"But the first theory is: it must be the shape."},{"time":190000,"text":"And that’s a perfectly reasonable theory in the sense that"},{"time":192000,"text":"almost everything else in biology works by shape."},{"time":194000,"text":"Enzymes that chew things up, antibodies, it’s all, you know,"},{"time":198000,"text":"the fit between a protein and whatever it is grabbing, in this case a smell."},{"time":204000,"text":"And I will try and explain to you what’s wrong with this notion."}]},{"cues":[{"time":207000,"text":"And the other theory is that we smell molecular vibrations."},{"time":210000,"text":"Now, this is a totally insane idea."},{"time":212000,"text":"And when I first came across it in the early '90s, I thought my predecessor,"},{"time":216000,"text":"Malcolm Dyson and Bob Wright, had really taken leave of their senses,"},{"time":219000,"text":"and I’ll explain to you why this was the case."},{"time":222000,"text":"However, I came to realize gradually that they may be right --"},{"time":225000,"text":"and I have to convince all my colleagues that this is so, but I’m working on it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":228000,"text":"Here’s how shape works in normal receptors."},{"time":234000,"text":"You have a molecule coming in, it gets into the protein, which is schematic here,"},{"time":239000,"text":"and it causes this thing to switch, to turn, to move in some way"},{"time":244000,"text":"by binding in certain parts."},{"time":248000,"text":"And the attraction, the forces, between the molecule and the protein"},{"time":250000,"text":"cause the motion. This is a shape-based idea."}]},{"cues":[{"time":255000,"text":"Now, what’s wrong with shape is summarized in this slide."},{"time":259000,"text":"The way --I expect everybody to memorize these compounds."},{"time":264000,"text":"This is one page of work from a chemist’s workbook, OK?"},{"time":269000,"text":"Working for a fragrance company."},{"time":271000,"text":"He’s making 45 molecules, and he’s looking for a sandalwood,"},{"time":274000,"text":"something that smells of sandalwood."},{"time":275000,"text":"Because there’s a lot of money in sandalwoods."},{"time":277000,"text":"And of these 45 molecules, only 4629 actually smells of sandalwood."},{"time":284000,"text":"And he puts an exclamation mark, OK? This is an awful lot of work.\n"},{"time":287000,"text":"This actually is roughly, in man-years of work, 200,000 dollars roughly,"},{"time":292000,"text":"if you keep them on the low salaries with no benefits."},{"time":296000,"text":"So this is a profoundly inefficient process."},{"time":298000,"text":"And my definition of a theory is, it’s not just something"},{"time":301000,"text":"that you teach people; it’s labor saving."},{"time":303000,"text":"A theory is something that enables you to do less work."},{"time":306000,"text":"I love the idea of doing less work. So let me explain to you why -- a very simple fact"},{"time":312000,"text":"that tells you why this shape theory really does not work very well."}]},{"cues":[{"time":317000,"text":"This is cis-3-hexene-1-ol. It smells of cut grass."},{"time":322000,"text":"This is cis-3-hexene-1-thiol, and this smells of rotten eggs, OK?"},{"time":329000,"text":"Now, you will have noticed that vodka never smells of rotten eggs."},{"time":334000,"text":"If it does, you put the glass down, you go to a different bar."},{"time":338000,"text":"This is -- in other words, we never get the O-H --"},{"time":343000,"text":"we never mistake it for an S-H, OK?"},{"time":346000,"text":"Like, at no concentration, even pure, you know,"},{"time":349000,"text":"if you smelt pure ethanol, it doesn’t smell of rotten eggs."},{"time":352000,"text":"Conversely, there is no concentration at which the sulfur compound will smell like vodka."},{"time":359000,"text":"It’s very hard to explain this by molecular recognition.\n"},{"time":363000,"text":"Now, I showed this to a physicist friend of mine who has a profound distaste"},{"time":365000,"text":"for biology, and he says, \"That’s easy! The things are a different color!\""},{"time":369000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":374000,"text":"We have to go a little beyond that. Now let me explain why vibrational theory has"},{"time":379000,"text":"some sort of interest in it. These molecules, as you saw in the beginning,"},{"time":383000,"text":"the building blocks had springs connecting them to each other."},{"time":385000,"text":"In fact, molecules are able to vibrate at a set of frequencies"},{"time":388000,"text":"which are very specific for each molecule and for the bonds connecting them."}]},{"cues":[{"time":392000,"text":"So this is the sound of the O-H stretch, translated into the audible range."},{"time":401000,"text":"S-H, quite a different frequency."},{"time":403000,"text":"Now, this is kind of interesting, because it tells you"},{"time":407000,"text":"that you should be looking for a particular fact, which is this:"},{"time":410000,"text":"nothing in the world smells like rotten eggs except S-H, OK?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":414000,"text":"Now, Fact B: nothing in the world has that frequency except S-H."},{"time":421000,"text":"If you look on this, imagine a piano keyboard."},{"time":423000,"text":"The S-H stretch is in the middle of a part of the keyboard"},{"time":427000,"text":"that has been, so to speak, damaged,"},{"time":429000,"text":"and there are no neighboring notes, nothing is close to it."},{"time":432000,"text":"You have a unique smell, a unique vibration.\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":434000,"text":"So I went searching when I started in this game"},{"time":436000,"text":"to convince myself that there was any degree of plausibility"},{"time":439000,"text":"to this whole crazy story."},{"time":441000,"text":"I went searching for a type of molecule, any molecule,"},{"time":444000,"text":"that would have that vibration and that -- the obvious prediction"},{"time":449000,"text":"was that it should absolutely smell of sulfur."},{"time":451000,"text":"If it didn’t, the whole idea was toast, and I might as well move on to other things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":457000,"text":"Now, after searching high and low for several months,"},{"time":461000,"text":"I discovered that there was a type of molecule called a Borane"},{"time":466000,"text":"which has exactly the same vibration."},{"time":468000,"text":"Now the good news is, Boranes you can get hold of."},{"time":471000,"text":"The bad news is they’re rocket fuels."},{"time":474000,"text":"Most of them explode spontaneously in contact with air,"},{"time":477000,"text":"and when you call up the companies, they only give you minimum ten tons, OK?"},{"time":481000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":484000,"text":"So this was not what they call a laboratory-scale experiment,\n"},{"time":487000,"text":"and they wouldn’t have liked it at my college."}]},{"cues":[{"time":489000,"text":"However, I managed to get a hold of a Borane eventually, and here is the beast."},{"time":497000,"text":"And it really does have the same -- if you calculate,"},{"time":499000,"text":"if you measure the vibrational frequencies, they are the same as S-H."}]},{"cues":[{"time":503000,"text":"Now, does it smell of sulfur? Well, if you go back in the literature,"},{"time":508000,"text":"there’s a man who knew more about Boranes than anyone"},{"time":511000,"text":"alive then or since, Alfred Stock, he synthesized all of them."},{"time":516000,"text":"And in an enormous 40-page paper in German he says, at one point --"},{"time":522000,"text":"my wife is German and she translated it for me --"},{"time":525000,"text":"and at one point he says, \"ganz widerlich Geruch,\"\n"},{"time":527000,"text":"an \"absolutely repulsive smell,\" which is good. Reminiscent of hydrogen sulfide."},{"time":533000,"text":"So this fact that Boranes smell of sulfur"},{"time":536000,"text":"had been known since 1910, and utterly forgotten until 1997, 1998."}]},{"cues":[{"time":543000,"text":"Now, the slight fly in the ointment is this: that"},{"time":547000,"text":"if we smell molecular vibrations, we must have a spectroscope in our nose."},{"time":552000,"text":"Now, this is a spectroscope, OK, on my laboratory bench."},{"time":557000,"text":"And it’s fair to say that if you look up somebody’s nose,"},{"time":559000,"text":"you’re unlikely to see anything resembling this."},{"time":562000,"text":"And this is the main objection to the theory."}]},{"cues":[{"time":564000,"text":"OK, great, we smell vibrations. How? All right?"},{"time":569000,"text":"Now when people ask this kind of question, they neglect something,"},{"time":571000,"text":"which is that physicists are really clever, unlike biologists."},{"time":575000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":578000,"text":"This is a joke. I’m a biologist, OK?"},{"time":580000,"text":"So it’s a joke against myself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":581000,"text":"Bob Jacklovich and John Lamb at Ford Motor Company,"},{"time":584000,"text":"in the days when Ford Motor was spending vast amounts of money"},{"time":586000,"text":"on fundamental research, discovered a way"},{"time":590000,"text":"to build a spectroscope that was intrinsically nano-scale."},{"time":594000,"text":"In other words, no mirrors, no lasers, no prisms, no nonsense,"},{"time":597000,"text":"just a tiny device, and he built this device. And this device uses electron tunneling."},{"time":602000,"text":"Now, I could do the dance of electron tunneling,"},{"time":605000,"text":"but I’ve done a video instead, which is much more interesting. Here’s how it works."}]},{"cues":[{"time":610000,"text":"Electrons are fuzzy creatures, and they can jump across gaps,"},{"time":614000,"text":"but only at equal energy. If the energy differs, they can’t jump."},{"time":619000,"text":"Unlike us, they won’t fall off the cliff."},{"time":621000,"text":"OK. Now. If something absorbs the energy, the electron can travel."},{"time":628000,"text":"So here you have a system, you have something --"},{"time":631000,"text":"and there’s plenty of that stuff in biology --"},{"time":632000,"text":"some substance giving an electron, and the electron tries to jump,"},{"time":637000,"text":"and only when a molecule comes along that has the right vibration"},{"time":641000,"text":"does the reaction happen, OK?"},{"time":643000,"text":"This is the basis for the device that these two guys at Ford built."}]},{"cues":[{"time":647000,"text":"And every single part of this mechanism is actually plausible in biology."},{"time":654000,"text":"In other words, I’ve taken off-the-shelf components,"},{"time":655000,"text":"and I’ve made a spectroscope."},{"time":657000,"text":"What’s nice about this idea, if you have a philosophical bent of mind,"},{"time":661000,"text":"is that then it tells you that the nose,"},{"time":663000,"text":"the ear and the eye are all vibrational senses."},{"time":666000,"text":"Of course, it doesn’t matter, because it could also be that they’re not."},{"time":670000,"text":"But it has a certain --"},{"time":671000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":673000,"text":"-- it has a certain ring to it which is attractive to people"},{"time":677000,"text":"who read too much 19th-century German literature."}]},{"cues":[{"time":681000,"text":"And then a magnificent thing happened:"},{"time":682000,"text":"I left academia and joined the real world of business,"},{"time":688000,"text":"and a company was created around my ideas"},{"time":691000,"text":"to make new molecules using my method,"},{"time":694000,"text":"along the lines of, let’s put someone else’s money where your mouth is."},{"time":698000,"text":"And one of the first things that happened was"},{"time":702000,"text":"we started going around to fragrance companies"},{"time":704000,"text":"asking for what they needed, because, of course,"},{"time":708000,"text":"if you could calculate smell, you don’t need chemists."},{"time":710000,"text":"You need a computer, a Mac will do it, if you know how to program the thing right,"},{"time":714000,"text":"OK? So you can try a thousand molecules,"},{"time":718000,"text":"you can try ten thousand molecules in a weekend,"},{"time":721000,"text":"and then you only tell the chemists to make the right one."},{"time":724000,"text":"And so that’s a direct path to making new odorants."}]},{"cues":[{"time":728000,"text":"And one of the first things that happened was"},{"time":729000,"text":"we went to see some perfumers in France --"},{"time":731000,"text":"and here’s where I do my Charles Fleischer impression --"},{"time":733000,"text":"and one of them says, \"You cannot make a coumarin.\""},{"time":737000,"text":"He says to me, \"I bet you cannot make a coumarin.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":740000,"text":"Now, coumarin is a very common thing, a material,"},{"time":744000,"text":"in fragrance which is derived from a bean that comes from South America."},{"time":747000,"text":"And it is the classic synthetic aroma chemical, OK?"},{"time":751000,"text":"It’s the molecule that has made men’s fragrances"},{"time":755000,"text":"smell the way they do since 1881, to be exact."}]},{"cues":[{"time":758000,"text":"And the problem is it’s a carcinogen."},{"time":761000,"text":"So nobody likes particularly to -- you know, aftershave with carcinogens."},{"time":767000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":769000,"text":"There are some reckless people, but it’s not worth it, OK?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":772000,"text":"So they asked us to make a new coumarin. And so we started doing calculations."},{"time":777000,"text":"And the first thing you do is you calculate the vibrational spectrum"},{"time":780000,"text":"of coumarin, and you smooth it out,"},{"time":781000,"text":"so that you have a nice picture of what the sort of chord, so to speak, of coumarin is."},{"time":787000,"text":"And then you start cranking the computer to find other molecules,"},{"time":793000,"text":"related or unrelated, that have the same vibrations."}]},{"cues":[{"time":796000,"text":"And we actually, in this case, I’m sorry to say,"},{"time":800000,"text":"it happened -- it was serendipitous."},{"time":802000,"text":"Because I got a phone call from our chief chemist"},{"time":805000,"text":"and he said, look, I’ve just found this such a beautiful reaction,"},{"time":810000,"text":"that even if this compound doesn’t smell of coumarin,"},{"time":811000,"text":"I want to do it, it’s just such a nifty,"},{"time":814000,"text":"one step -- I mean, chemists have weird minds --"},{"time":817000,"text":"one step, 90 percent yield, you know, and you get this lovely"},{"time":821000,"text":"crystalline compound. Let us try it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":823000,"text":"And I said, first of all, let me do the calculation on that compound, bottom right,"},{"time":827000,"text":"which is related to coumarin, but has an extra pentagon inserted into the molecule."},{"time":833000,"text":"Calculate the vibrations, the purple spectrum is that new fellow,"},{"time":838000,"text":"the white one is the old one."},{"time":839000,"text":"And the prediction is it should smell of coumarin."},{"time":843000,"text":"They made it ... and it smelled exactly like coumarin."},{"time":851000,"text":"And this is our new baby, called tonkene."},{"time":856000,"text":"You see, when you’re a scientist, you’re always selling ideas."},{"time":858000,"text":"And people are very resistant to ideas, and rightly so."},{"time":862000,"text":"Why should new ideas be accepted?"},{"time":864000,"text":"But when you put a little 10-gram vial on the table in front of perfumers"},{"time":870000,"text":"and it smells like coumarin, and it isn’t coumarin,"},{"time":872000,"text":"and you’ve found it in three weeks,"},{"time":874000,"text":"this focuses everybody’s mind wonderfully."},{"time":877000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":878000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":884000,"text":"And people often ask me, is your theory accepted?"},{"time":888000,"text":"And I said, well, by whom? I mean most, you know -- there’s three attitudes:"},{"time":893000,"text":"You’re right, and I don’t know why, which is the most rational one at this point."},{"time":897000,"text":"You’re right, and I don’t care how you do it, in a sense;"},{"time":901000,"text":"you bring me the molecules, you know."},{"time":902000,"text":"And: You’re completely wrong, and I’m sure you’re completely wrong."}]},{"cues":[{"time":905000,"text":"OK? Now, we’re dealing with people who only want results,"},{"time":908000,"text":"and this is the commercial world."},{"time":910000,"text":"And they tell us that even if we do it by astrology, they’re happy."},{"time":915000,"text":"But we’re not actually doing it by astrology."},{"time":918000,"text":"But for the last three years, I’ve had what I consider to be"},{"time":920000,"text":"the best job in the entire universe, which is to put my hobby --"},{"time":925000,"text":"which is, you know, fragrance and all the magnificent things --"},{"time":927000,"text":"plus a little bit of biophysics, a small amount of self-taught chemistry"},{"time":932000,"text":"at the service of something that actually works."}]},{"cues":[{"time":934000,"text":"Thank you very much."},{"time":935000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}